reviewText: STARRBOOTY starring RuPaul is a sick, twisted, and utterly amazing film.  As Starrbooty, RuPaul reminds that she is the real Supermodel of the World.  She works it, pouts it, and pounds it--it's truly a sight to see.  The plot?  Well Starrbooty must save her niece from the clutches of Annaka Manners.  Along the way there's a lot to do and be done...all with plenty of full frontal from some of gay porn's finest leading men.The film is trashy camp--a wonderful genre of film for the freaks of the world.  The dialouge is full on cheese, much of it pays hommage to films of the past, a true camp marker.  The makeup and costumes are amazing, with RuPaul and cast wearing each with ease.It's hard to disect this film, and it's essential un-reviewable.  It's full of sex, violence, and is not suitable for the faint of heart.  "Starrbooty" is also essentially gay cinema but hopefully out hetero counterparts will find some sense of humor in this camp coated masterpiece.
summary: Sick and Twisted--Just The Way I Like It!

reviewText: Starrbooty is a raunchy, outrageous, campy, offensive and completely hilarious b-movie. This is low budget gorilla filmmaking (don't expect an anamorphic image). The plot is paper thin, the acting can be spotty, technically the film is no where near the quality you'd see from an A-list Hollywood studio, but surprisingly none of that matters. The movie is a laugh riot! So much so that some of the jokes aren't heard on your first viewing because you are laughing over them.All the low budget trappings fit perfectly with Starrbootys anti-establishment, middle finger gesturing attitude. Does any of this sound familiar?  This is the kind of film John Waters would have made back in the day.  What a thrill to see that spirit alive, kicking, screaming and demanding your attention.This DVD includes deleted scenes, a blooper reel, music videos, snippets from a few selected film festivals as well as cast and crew interviews about making the movie.  The interviews keep the campy spirit alive and are throughly entertaining on thier own.  This is the DVD of the year for fans of counter cluture, camp and bootylicious humor.  We can only hope that this is the start of a whole series of films from Ru and Company.

reviewText: STARRBOOTY is an instant camp classic!  It ranks right up there with "Female Trouble" and "Vegas in Space"!  RuPaul is one of the most underrated entertainers of our time.  In STARRBOOTY, he fuses the splendor of blaxploitation cinema with the trashy stylings of the John Waters movies to create a hilarious romp through the gutter.  Drag queens, hookers, porn stars, and "Mommie Dearest" references abound!  RuPaul first played STARRBOOTY back in the 1980's and his hooker character has also been seen on his VH1 talk show back in the 1990's.One can only hope that STARRBOOTY spawns a franchise and there are many sequels ahead!  And I hope a soundtrack CD isn't far behind.  The music is classic RuPaul with a nasty twist!  Work It!

reviewText: Among the small but growing number of drag queen movies being released, one of my favorites is Starrbooty, a campy take on the Pam Grier blaxploitation films of the 1970s.  RuPaul plays Starrbooty, a multi-talented special agent who goes undercover as a prostitute to infiltrate an evil cosmetics company.  Crude and raunchy, it features some scenes that would basically be pornographic if they weren't played for laughs, revealing a different side of RuPaul, who is far more family-friendly on her show RuPaul's Drag Race.  A couple of scenes, particular among the musical interludes and fights, were too long and perfunctory, but in general I loved the uncompromisingly, uninhibitedly campy and outrageous humor.
